Shield, denial-of-service protection.

Shield protects A-W-S resources from distributed denial-of-service attacks, and it comes in two tiers.

Shield Standard is automatic, free, and on for every A-W-S account. It defends Layer three and Layer four, that's SYN floods, U-D-P reflection, and volumetric attacks, for resources behind CloudFront, Route 53, Elastic Load Balancers, and E-C-2 Elastic I-Ps. There is nothing to configure; A-W-S absorbs the routine flood traffic before it ever reaches your infrastructure.

Shield Advanced is a paid subscription at three thousand dollars per organisation per month, plus data transfer, and it builds on Standard with several things worth memorising. First, Layer seven protection, defending application-layer floods like H-T-T-P GET and POST floods and slowloris against CloudFront, A-L-B, and A-P-I Gateway; Standard only covers Layer three and four. Second, denial-of-service cost protection: A-W-S credits back the scaling charges on E-C-2, E-L-B, CloudFront, and Route 53 that you incur because of an active attack, and without it a successful absorption can still arrive with a six-figure bill. Third, twenty-four-seven access to the Shield Response Team, the S-R-T, A-W-S denial-of-service experts you can reach during an attack and pre-authorise to act on your account. And fourth, advanced real-time metrics, reporting, and global threat dashboards.

The exam cues are clean. Free, automatic, Layer three and four, that's Shield Standard. Layer seven protection, cost protection, the Shield Response Team, or a surprise bill after an attack, that's Shield Advanced. Remember that Shield defends availability, while W-A-F, coming up next, inspects content; the two layer together at the edge.
